refactor: extract and consolidate CLI utilities to eliminate code duplication

Created shared CLI utilities module to consolidate duplicate code patterns
across CLI command files, reducing maintenance overhead and improving code reuse.

Changes:
- Create src/shard_markdown/cli/utils.py with shared utilities:
  * Single console instance for consistent CLI output formatting
  * handle_chromadb_errors() function consolidating error handling patterns
  * get_connected_chromadb_client() function unifying ChromaDB connection logic

- Refactor CLI command files to use shared utilities:
  * collections.py: Remove 22 lines of duplicate code (console + 2 utility functions)
  * query.py: Remove 20 lines of duplicate code (console + 2 utility functions)
  * config.py: Use shared console instance (1 line removed)
  * process.py: Use shared console instance (1 line removed)

- Add comprehensive test coverage for shared utilities:
  * 10 test cases covering all utility functions
  * Tests for console singleton behavior
  * Tests for error handling with different verbosity levels
  * Tests for ChromaDB connection success and failure scenarios

- Update existing tests to use new shared utilities module

Benefits:
- Eliminates ~44 lines of duplicate code across CLI modules
- Provides single source of truth for CLI utilities
- Maintains 100% backward compatibility
- Improves code maintainability through DRY principle
- Consistent error handling and console formatting across all CLI commands

issue.title: Phase 2: Extract and Consolidate CLI Utilities
issue.body:
## Overview
Create shared CLI utilities to eliminate duplicate code patterns across CLI command files.

## Scope
- **Risk Level**: Low (pure refactoring)
- **Estimated Effort**: 3-4 hours
- **Code Reduction**: ~200-300 lines

## Tasks
- [ ] Create `src/shard_markdown/cli/utils.py` with shared utilities:
  - [ ] Shared `console` instance (single Console() for all CLI commands)
  - [ ] `handle_chromadb_errors()` function (consolidate from collections.py:21-31 and query.py:19-31)
  - [ ] `get_connected_chromadb_client()` function (consolidate from multiple CLI commands)
- [ ] Update CLI command files to use shared utilities:
  - [ ] `cli/collections.py` - remove duplicate error handler
  - [ ] `cli/query.py` - remove duplicate error handler  
  - [ ] All CLI files - use shared console instance
- [ ] Run tests to ensure functionality is preserved
- [ ] Update imports across affected files

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Single shared console instance across all CLI commands
- [ ] No duplicate error handling functions
- [ ] No duplicate connection functions
- [ ] All tests pass
- [ ] No functional changes to CLI behavior
- [ ] Improved code maintainability

## Dependencies
- Should be completed after Phase 1 (dead code removal)

## Parent Issue
Related to #119 - Code cleanup

## Priority
**High** - Major maintainability improvement

issue.title: Supporting multiprocessing models other than fork(2)
issue.body:
Greetings everyone,

As seen with #250 , anything Python changes might render "legacy" getmail unsupported. The changes from Python 2 to 3 made it obvious, but so are changes made within Python 3 (especially the change from `fork` to `spawn`,  unforeseen to me on MacOS with Python 3.8, and more recently on 3.14).

In the current state, getmail will have trouble with spawn, which is a shared concern between various actors. For Python multiprocessing (using `spawn`), pickle will be used for ser/des when spawning subprocesses, and pickle is limited in the type of objects it can handle (as seen in #250 ). Supporting this requires an extensive cleanup of `logging`, `tempfile` usage and `SSLContext` in getmail, as these objects are not pickable. One would even argue about serializing sensitive objects like SSLContext, but in the current use case the impact negligible.

After looking at it yesterday, I see different paths forward, but each have their tradeoffs @rpuntaie :
- use force fork method, as [suggested in Python docs](https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html#contexts-and-start-methods). The tradeoff is that if getmail ends up multithreading "unknowingly" [like it might happen on MacOS with higher level libs](https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/77906), getmail will crash. (Note: the issue would be the exact same with the legacy method of os.fork(2) of getmail5);
- patch getmail classes to support spawn. From my short testing, it involves dropping the custom-made logging class and use Python logging module instead (which seems to be onpar feature-wise, [original comment](https://github.com/getmail6/getmail6/blob/83ca7adfaaef9482a887be5126d18f2c6feeb74e/getmailcore/logging.py#L7) does not seem to apply any more), redesign the temporary files communication between parent <> child, and prevent [SSLContext sharing between processes](https://github.com/getmail6/getmail6/blob/83ca7adfaaef9482a887be5126d18f2c6feeb74e/getmailcore/_retrieverbases.py#L126). Tradeoff: significant departure from legacy, and extensive testing ahead.
